<TEXT>
here is an example of the information the 
social security administration will provide in its new personal 
earnings and benefit estimate statement 
the figures are actual estimates for a 40yearold john q 
public based on a history of moderate wages for the past two 
decades 
this person born dec 16 1947 must wait until 66 to qualify 
for full social security retirement benefits 
he told social security he earned 23938 in 1987 expects to 
earn 23000 this year and the equivalent of 23000 in future 
years 
social security reported back that his earnings record showed 
nothing earned in 1963 and earlier and the following in social 
securitytaxed earnings and estimated taxes paid since then 
1964 632 22 
1965 497 18 
1966 3607 151 
1967 4053 178 
1968 3833 168 
1969 5282 253 
1970 6253 300 
1971 7142 371 
1972 8295 431 
1973 9001 526 
1974 10239 599 
1975 11163 653 
1976 11516 673 
1977 12663 740 
1978 13769 833 
1979 15158 929 
1989 17407 1067 
1981 18495 1229 
1982 20858 1397 
1983 22485 1506 
1984 25085 1680 
1985 26587 1874 
1986 25647 1833 
1987 not yet posted 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
then it provided the following retirement benefit estimates 
at age 62 a monthly benefit in todays dollars of 730 
at age 66 970 
at age 70 1285 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
survivors 
a surviving child could get 605 a month 
if a child and a surviving spouse caring for a child both 
qualify each could get 605 
the surviving spouse could receive 810 a month when she or her 
reaches full retirement age 
the maximum family benefit would be 1420 a month 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
disability 
this workers monthly disability check would be 805 
he and his family could receive up to 1205 a month 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the booklet will also explain the payroll tax rates currently 
751 percent on employees and employers and 1302 percent on the 
selfemployed the tax pays for both social security and medicare 
the brochures notes that currently the average monthly benefit 
for a retired worker 65 or older is 523 plus medicare benefits 
valued at 202 a month 
