<TEXT>
the palestinian uprising election year 
politics and protracted labor disputes are undermining israels 
economic recovery program by pushing up inflation and reducing 
growth 
industrial production is down 35 percent the first such drop 
in eight years and inflation is expected to exceed 20 percent up 
from 16 percent last year and a third higher than initially 
forecast 
we had to scale down our expectations after more optimistic 
projections in early 1988 said ruth lowental assistant director 
general of economic affairs in the finance ministry 
the gloomier prognosis is accompanied by a feeling of 
insecurity because nobody knows whats going to happen after the 
nov 1 national election said joseph canaan an israeli 
journalist who writes for two west german economic publications 
a key reason for the slump is the 8monthold arab uprising in 
the occupied west bank and gaza strip already has eaten up more 
than half of this years growth initially projected at 37 percent 
the uprising has cost more than 700 million in lost tourism 
uncollected taxes and additional military expenses said amnon 
neubach an economic adviser to foreign minister shimon peres 
in addition fewer of the 15 million palestinians in the 
occupied lands buy israeli products and about 20 percent of the 
110000 palestinians working in israel no longer report to their 
jobs as a result of a palestinian boycott 
when you have 15 million consumers who used to buy israeli 
products and they stopped doing it it has a serious effect 
said an israeli industrialist speaking on condition of anonymity 
stability is also threatened by increasing wage demands backed 
by numerous strikes by israeli workers excluding palestinian work 
stoppages the israeli economy lost 13 million work days due to 
strikes in 1987 more than triple the 1986 figure 
the labor disputes indicate workers are no longer willing to 
make the kind of sacrifices they accepted during a 1985 austerity 
program 
workers then accepted wage cuts of up to 20 percent to help stem 
soaring inflation and reduce a 3 billion budget deficit 
the program worked inflation dropped to 161 percent in 1987 
and the budget deficit fell from 136 percent of the gross domestic 
product of 12 billion shekels in 1984 to a surplus of 17 percent 
of the 1986 gdp of 13 billion shekels 812 million 
but in the past two years real wages have been rising faster 
than productivity heating up inflation and finance minister moshe 
nissim is under growing pressure to make concessions as the 
election campaign is heating up 
our basic target is to maintain stability ms lowental 
said but nobody knows whats going to happen with the wages 
still unsigned is a tentative agreement for an 11 percent wage 
increase over two years for the 450000 civil servants onethird 
of the civilian labor force also unresolved are private sector 
negotzed 
national health system with months of strikes and slowdowns 
the government agreed to emergency payments to ease the backlog 
of 15000 israelis waiting for operations but there has been 
little progress in wage talks for doctors who earn an average 700 
a month and are seeking wage hikes of more than 20 percent 
if the doctors get large increases it could affect the whole 
wage structure if you give higher wages to one group of people 
you have to give more to all the others said canaan 
nissim also is under pressure to devalue the israeli shekel 
which has been fixed at a rate of about 16 shekels to the dollar 
since the days of hyperinflation 
manufacturers complain the strong shekel is making it difficult 
for israeli exports to compete and is partly to blame for the drop 
in industrial production 
nissim has refused to devalue for fear of raising import prices 
and fueling inflation 
especially hard hit is koor the industrial conglomerate of the 
powerful histadrut trade union federation which lost 250 million 
in 1987 a record in israeli industry 
the united states which gives israel 12 billion a year in 
economic aid urged israel to sell off stateowned companies lower 
taxes and cut government spending 
the government has taken some steps in that direction but chaim 
barkai economics professor at hebrew university said no unpopular 
steps would be taken during the threemonth election campaign 
the government must close down unprofitable factories and cut 
spending but there wont be any changes in economic policy before 
the elections barkai said 
