<TEXT>
scientists and construction workers 
swarmed over this scenic sunbaked plateau thursday making final 
preparations for an historic ussoviet nuclear weapons 
verification experiment later this month 
us ambassador c paul robinson said the aug 17th test and 
another planned in the soviet union next month were a 
breakthrough in negotiations between the us and soviet union on 
nuclear testing 
it is unprecedented to be able to exchange this type of data 
said robinson the chief us negotiator at talks with the soviet 
union on nuclear testing 
reporters were taken thursday to the test site 130 miles 
northwest of las vegas for a daylong briefing and an impromptu 
news conference held on a platform fourtenths of a mile above the 
nuclear device 
the blast will have an explosive punch of up to 150 kilotons 
nearly 12 times the force of the atomic bomb that destroyed the 
japanese city of hiroshima 43 years ago saturday 
joe behne test director from lawrence livermore laboratories 
told the gathering that no one would be allowed within 15 miles of 
the site when the device is detonated 
the experiment is designed to test the ability of the united 
states and the soviet union to monitor the size of each others 
nuclear tests such monitoring is critical to comply with treaties 
limiting the size of nuclear tests under a policy of trust but 
verify 
treaties limiting tests to no more than 150 kilotons were passed 
in 1974 and 1976 but never ratified 
some three dozen soviet scientists will be on the nevada test 
site for this months blast codenamed kearsarge american 
scientists will monitor the september soviet test at semipalatinsk 
the device that will be detonated later this month was delivered 
july 20 and placed 180 feet above the bottom of a 2200foot 
vertical shaft 
the soviet scientists who have been on the nevada site since 
spring were not allowed to see the device itself according to 
behne 
but the soviets were allowed to examine the 8foot canister 
holding the device once the container painted red white and blue 
was sealed 
the joint verification experiment will focus on cables half an 
inch in diameter running to the site of detonation from instrument 
trailers hundreds of yards away and down to the device itself 
additional cables are placed in a second hole 30 feet away from and 
parallel to the weapon shaft 
the tests come two years after president reagan proposed using a 
system called corrtex which is designed to measure the size of a 
nuclear blast by the shock waves emitted from the nuclear device 
the soviets will be using a similar system of their own called 
miz and a second system which takes similar measurements 
the joint tests are to determine whether the two monitoring 
systems are compatible and whether explosions can be monitored by 
having the cables only in the second hole 
the sticking point for both countries has been the idea of 
allowing one country to place monitoring cables in the same hole as 
the device itself 
the breakthrough on the test verification issue came late last 
year in talks at geneva when both sides agreed to exchange 
scientists and monitor a test at each site officials say that if 
the monitoring systems work each country could have scientists at 
the others nuclear test site for all future tests 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

