<TEXT>
the house on thursday gave lopsided bipartisan 
approval to a 71 billion electionyear package of minor tax 
changes that would benefit farmers mutualfund owners freelance 
writers and rural mail carriers 
the targeted tax cuts would be financed by higher taxes on 
defense contractors certain other corporations pipe smokers and 
purchasers of singlepremium life insurance policies 
the 38025 vote for the bill was easily the widest margin by 
which any tax legislation has been approved over the last decade 
voting for the measure were 230 democrats and 150 republicans 6 
democrats and 19 republicans voted no 
the bill now goes to the senate where the finance committee has 
approved a strippeddown version 
the chief purpose of the 960page house bill is to correct 
errors and clear up ambiguities in the landmark tax overhaul enaced 
in 1986 since this is almost certainly the only tax bill with a 
chance of becoming law this year the ways and means committee used 
it to carry dozens of substantive tax changes 
despite its size the bill is one of the smallest pieces of tax 
legislation in recent years the joint committee on taxation 
estimates it would cut taxes by about 71 billion through 1991 and 
raise taxes by about 47 million less than that amount 
nevertheless rep dan rostenkowski dill committee chairman 
told the house this bill is in keeping with the spirit of tax 
reform 
he and rep bill archer of texas senior republican on the 
committee emphasized that unlike most tax bills of recent years 
the legislation includes no tax breaks that are targeted for the 
benefit of only one or two individuals or corporations 
among the dozens of provisions are those to 
